n of Valor and A Woman Large of Head: Matchmaking in the Ancient Near East -- tThe Fly and the Dog: Observations on Ideational Polarity in the Book of Qoheleth -- tA Sense of Timing: A Neglected Aspect of Qoheleth’s Wisdom -- tThe Little Sister and Solomon’s Vineyard: Song of Songs 8:8–12 as a Lovers’ Dialogue -- tAnswering Questions, Questioning Answers: The Rhetoric of Interrogatives in the Speeches of Job and His Friends -- tPart 2 “Preserving the Sayings of the Famous” (Sirach 39:2): Text, Versions, and Method -- tThe Mysterious Disappearance of Zerubbabel -- tTextual Criticism of the Book of Deuteronomy and the Oxford Hebrew Bible Project -- tWhat’s in a Name? Contemporization and Toponyms in LXX-Isaiah -- tCharacterization in the Old Greek of Job -- tOn the Influence of Job on Jewish Hellenistic Literature -- tBecoming Canon: Women, Texts, and Scribes in Proverbs and Sirach -- tTranslating Biblical Words of Wisdom into the Modern World -- tThe Text-Critical Value of the Septuagint of Proverbs -- tChristian Aramaism: The Birth and Growth of Aramaic Scholarship in the Sixteenth Century -- tSpying out the Land: A Report from Genology -- tWhat’s in a Calendar? Calendar Conformity, Calendar Controversy, and Calendar Reform in Ancient and Medieval Judaism -- tCompeting Commentaries -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMichael V. Fox, long-time professor in the Dept. of Hebrew and Semitic Studies at the University of Wisconsin—Madison, is known both for his scholarship and his teaching. As the editors of this volume in his honor note, the care and sensitivity of his reading of the Hebrew text are well known, and he lavishes equal attention on his own writing, to the benefit of all who read his work, which now includes the first of two volumes in the Anchor Bible commentary on Proverbs (the next volume is in preparation), as well as monographs on wisdom literature in ancient Israel and elsewhere, and many articles. The rigor that he brought to his own work he also inflicted on his students, and they and a number of his colleagues honor him with their contributions to this volume.Contributors include: Menahem Haran, Kelvin G. Friebel, Cynthia L. Miller, Theron Young, Adele Berlin, William P. Brown, James L. Crenshaw, John A. Cook, Robert D. Holmstedt, Shamir Yona, Christine Roy Yoder, Carol R. Fontaine, Nili Shupak, Victor Avigdor Horowitz, Tova Forti, Richard L. Schultz, J. Cheryl Exum, Dennis R. Magary, Theodore J. Lewis, Sidnie White Crawford, Ronald L. Troxel, Karl V. Kutz, Heidi M. Szpek, Claudia V. Camp, Johann Cook, Leonard Greenspoon, Stephen G. Burnett, Carol A. Newsom, Shemaryahu Talmon, and Frederick E. Greenspahn.The book is organized around themes that reflect Prof. Fox’s interests and work: Part 1: “Seeking Out Wisdom and Concerned with Prophecies” (Sir 39:1): Studies in Biblical Texts”; Part 2: “Preserving the Sayings of the Famous” (Sir 39:2): Text, Versions, and Method.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAvigdor Hurowitz, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlin, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, William P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnett, Stephen G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamp, Claudia V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheryl Exum, J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Johann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrenshaw, James L